I. Security Alert
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Because our readers are important to us, we constantly scour the
media and news outlets to keep you up to date on all issues of
potential concern.

Everyone knows the importance of securing his/her personal
and/or business information in today’s world.

Today it’s: spam, viruses, trojans, spyware, online fraud schemes,
phishing, pharming, worms, bots (malicious code that turns PC’s
and servers into remotely controlled zombies) zero-day exploits,
and more.

But, do you realize that cybercrime has accelerated from hackers
to organized crime? Some sources state that, for as little
as $1, critical personal information can be compromised, and,
based upon stories by those affected, it takes years, and, often
personal time and investment, sometimes including attorneys’
fees, to clear up.

Intrusions have the potential to advance into areas such as:
printers, instant messaging community Web sites like MySpace,
corporate networks, voting machines, passwords, mobile devices,
cell phones, blackberries, usb drives, thumb drives, flash drives,
discarded hard drives, and some of the newer photocopiers
that have data storage.

According to some sources, a laptop is stolen nearly every minute
in the USA, and few are ever recovered. Because of hacker hotspots,
mobile and at-home workers need to use caution when connecting
laptops at hotels, airports, libraries, and, when intermingling work
data with personal data on their at-home connections.

Assume nothing when it comes to security. Scan usb drives that
you may have received at trade shows; when discarding or having
your cell phone repaired, carefully follow all manufacturers’
instructions about data removal. While we don’t want you to become
paranoid, never let your guard down.

Update security software; be wary of sites visited; and, although it
may be tempting, never open emails from an unknown source.

Look over both shoulders, up, down, and all-around. The data
you save could be your own. Eternal vigilance has its rewards.

